00:23:12,710 --> 00:23:13,740
(Although they are characters
from the opposite side of the world,)

526
00:23:13,740 --> 00:23:16,510
It makes me rather nervous
to draw in front of a child.

527
00:23:16,510 --> 00:23:19,319
(but he does his best,
and they watch quietly.)

528
00:23:20,419 --> 00:23:21,990
(Let's go together, Porfi!)

529
00:23:22,790 --> 00:23:25,119
(They kick a ball around together...)

530
00:23:25,119 --> 00:23:26,819
(and laugh together.)

531
00:23:26,819 --> 00:23:28,020
They look happy.

532
00:23:29,290 --> 00:23:33,099
(They became close very quickly.)

533
00:23:34,030 --> 00:23:37,300
(A friendship transcending
a 29-year age difference)

534
00:23:37,300 --> 00:23:39,639
- High five.
- It looks so nice.

535
00:23:39,639 --> 00:23:40,839
(It's coming soon.)

536
00:23:42,240 --> 00:23:43,409
He's like my son.

537
00:23:44,879 --> 00:23:46,409
(They're still awkward.)

538
00:23:46,409 --> 00:23:48,109
It's hard.

539
00:23:52,849 --> 00:23:55,250
You draw the rest.

540
00:23:56,149 --> 00:23:58,020
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

541
00:23:59,059 --> 00:24:00,760
(Porfi Junior will draw the rest.)

542
00:24:00,760 --> 00:24:02,230
He stopped drawing halfway.

543
00:24:02,230 --> 00:24:03,790
- It was tough.
- He stopped drawing Kim Doo Chi halfway.

544
00:24:03,790 --> 00:24:06,760
I hiked for too long.

545
00:24:08,369 --> 00:24:10,700
- Let's go to the valley.
- Okay.

546
00:24:10,700 --> 00:24:13,700
Porfi said he would show me
around his house.

547
00:24:16,639 --> 00:24:18,909
- Banana tree.
- Banana tree.

548
00:24:18,909 --> 00:24:21,579
It needs to grow taller.

549
00:24:21,579 --> 00:24:23,780
- Fruit?
- Fruit?

550
00:24:23,780 --> 00:24:25,119
It's a fruit tree.

551
00:24:25,119 --> 00:24:26,419
(He roughly understands
that it's a fruit tree.)

552
00:24:26,579 --> 00:24:27,919
(Following)

553
00:24:28,149 --> 00:24:31,089
I wash here.

554
00:24:31,089 --> 00:24:32,589
- Drink?
- Yes.

555
00:24:32,589 --> 00:24:34,119
I can drink.

556
00:24:34,119 --> 00:24:37,030
- Is the water clean?
- It's fantastic. You can just drink it.

557
00:24:37,490 --> 00:24:38,730
Is there any water you don't drink?

558
00:24:38,730 --> 00:24:40,629
You even drank water from Lake Titicaca.

559
00:24:40,629 --> 00:24:42,599
(South America's sommelier
that tastes every water he comes across)

560
00:24:43,270 --> 00:24:45,540
(He hydrates his mouth.)

561
00:24:47,669 --> 00:24:50,869
(He hydrates his skin.)

562
00:24:52,210 --> 00:24:54,510
- Give me a moment.
- Okay.

563
00:24:54,510 --> 00:24:56,210
(He starts recharging in earnest.)

564
00:24:56,210 --> 00:24:58,780
I was sweating the whole day.

565
00:24:59,319 --> 00:25:01,819
- It's great, right?
- It's great.

566
00:25:03,050 --> 00:25:04,250
The water's so cool.

567
00:25:06,089 --> 00:25:07,159
Porfi.

568
00:25:07,159 --> 00:25:09,359
(On the way to the valley after hydrating)

569
00:25:10,889 --> 00:25:12,000
Porfi.

570
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:13,460
(Porfi suddenly stops.)

571
00:25:13,460 --> 00:25:15,169
My son is coming over there.

572
00:25:15,899 --> 00:25:17,369
- Your son?
- Yes.

573
00:25:18,599 --> 00:25:20,569
(Porfi's first son is crossing over
on the zipline.)

574
00:25:20,569 --> 00:25:21,909
He must be on his way back from school.

575
00:25:22,270 --> 00:25:23,770
- Unbelievable.
- The first son.

576
00:25:23,770 --> 00:25:25,909
The eldest son is coming back from school.

577
00:25:25,909 --> 00:25:27,680
(Porfi's first son is crossing over
on the zipline.)

578
00:25:27,680 --> 00:25:29,050
- This is his way back home?
- That's amazing.

579
00:25:29,450 --> 00:25:31,680
- You have three sons?
- Yes.

580
00:25:31,680 --> 00:25:34,480
- Three Porfis?
- Yes.

581
00:25:38,050 --> 00:25:40,490
(They climb down to welcome him.)

582
00:25:40,760 --> 00:25:42,960
(A familiar road)

583
00:25:42,960 --> 00:25:44,030
Gosh.

584
00:25:44,030 --> 00:25:47,059
(I'm not familiar with it.)

585
00:25:47,059 --> 00:25:48,260
Goodness.

586
00:25:49,230 --> 00:25:52,770
Now, Porfi the First...

587
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:54,470
Porfi the First...

588
00:25:54,470 --> 00:25:57,940
is going down to greet his son.

589
00:25:59,109 --> 00:26:01,040
(I'm home. Welcome.)

590
00:26:01,040 --> 00:26:02,680
He crossed over using the zipline.

591
00:26:04,079 --> 00:26:05,649
- He's my son.
- Your son.

592
00:26:05,649 --> 00:26:08,819
- He is Elmer.
- Elmer.

593
00:26:09,290 --> 00:26:12,419
He's good at mathematics.

594
00:26:12,760 --> 00:26:14,389
You're good at mathematics too?

595
00:26:14,389 --> 00:26:16,059
He's good.

596
00:26:16,290 --> 00:26:18,230
The child feels rather shy.

597
00:26:20,159 --> 00:26:22,069
But his eyes look brave.

598
00:26:22,599 --> 00:26:25,200
(After showing off his son,
they continue to head to the valley.)

599
00:26:25,200 --> 00:26:27,669
Guys, the way down is...

600
00:26:28,609 --> 00:26:31,069
- Be careful.
- Bolivia's...

601
00:26:31,069 --> 00:26:32,809
If you trip, you'll fall off.

602
00:26:33,680 --> 00:26:34,710
I understand.

603
00:26:35,010 --> 00:26:37,349
My goodness. You must stay alert.

604
00:26:37,349 --> 00:26:42,450
(Kian84 follows Porfi.)

605
00:26:44,490 --> 00:26:46,220
- The slope...
- It's beautiful.

606
00:26:46,220 --> 00:26:48,359
Oh, gosh.

607
00:26:49,190 --> 00:26:50,829
(Lying down)

608
00:26:52,829 --> 00:26:54,000
It's beautiful.

609
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:55,869
- Oh, gosh.
- My goodness.

610
00:26:58,099 --> 00:26:59,500
It's beautiful!

611
00:27:00,740 --> 00:27:02,869
- It's beautiful!
- You're a good friend.

612
00:27:03,169 --> 00:27:04,369
You're a good friend.

613
00:27:04,369 --> 00:27:05,480
You kept saying, "It's beautiful."

614
00:27:05,480 --> 00:27:08,079
He invited me, so I can't say
that it hurts from falling down.

615
00:27:08,079 --> 00:27:10,879
- He suddenly says it's pretty.
- You're kind.

616
00:27:12,180 --> 00:27:18,889
(After walking for a long time,)

617
00:27:18,889 --> 00:27:21,389
(they can finally see the valley.)

618
00:27:21,389 --> 00:27:23,859
He is showing us his secret garden.

619
00:27:24,790 --> 00:27:26,859
Guys. Gosh.

620
00:27:29,930 --> 00:27:31,129
It's amazing.

621
00:27:31,129 --> 00:27:35,669
(Porfi's secret valley
heals you automatically.)

622
00:27:35,669 --> 00:27:37,169
I'm envious of that.

623
00:27:38,710 --> 00:27:40,210
It's so nice.

624
00:27:41,010 --> 00:27:42,250
This is the valley.

625
00:27:42,649 --> 00:27:44,909
We wash our clothes here.

626
00:27:44,909 --> 00:27:46,379
You wash your clothes here.

627
00:27:46,520 --> 00:27:50,050
I want to make a swimming pool there.

628
00:27:50,050 --> 00:27:51,520
I'm planning to make it in the future.

629
00:27:51,520 --> 00:27:54,419
You want to turn this
into your secret garden.

630
00:27:54,419 --> 00:27:57,889
He wants to turn it into his garden.

631
00:27:57,889 --> 00:27:59,059
(We look forward
to Porfi's upgraded secret garden.)

632
00:27:59,059 --> 00:28:00,430
I was really envious of this.

633
00:28:00,599 --> 00:28:01,629
It's beautiful.

634
00:28:02,270 --> 00:28:03,899
Let's go.

635
00:28:03,899 --> 00:28:05,599
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

636
00:28:05,599 --> 00:28:08,399
(They finish looking around the valley
and go back home.)

637
00:28:10,669 --> 00:28:12,780
(He starts showing his house in earnest.)

638
00:28:14,109 --> 00:28:16,809
Porfi says he is going to show me
around his house.

639
00:28:17,109 --> 00:28:18,480
So let's follow him.

640
00:28:19,349 --> 00:28:20,379
This is...

641
00:28:20,379 --> 00:28:22,389
(A chicken coop)

642
00:28:22,389 --> 00:28:24,649
(It's empty.)

643
00:28:24,649 --> 00:28:27,389
Wild animals stole them away.

644
00:28:27,520 --> 00:28:31,829
Leopard cats must've stolen them all.

645
00:28:32,760 --> 00:28:35,129
How does everything seem similar
to my relative's house?

646
00:28:36,230 --> 00:28:37,970
(This is the master bedroom.)

647
00:28:37,970 --> 00:28:42,309
This is Porfi and his wife's room.

648
00:28:42,309 --> 00:28:43,770
I sleep on this side.

649
00:28:45,339 --> 00:28:47,010
This is an old laptop.

650
00:28:47,010 --> 00:28:49,809
- It's a laptop?
- Yes, he had a laptop.

651
00:28:49,809 --> 00:28:51,649
Laptop. Can you play games?

652
00:28:52,349 --> 00:28:53,980
It's very old.

653
00:28:53,980 --> 00:28:56,389
Show me. This is...

654
00:28:56,389 --> 00:28:57,649
(It makes a loud noise
as soon as it is turned on.)

655
00:28:57,649 --> 00:28:59,690
- Did it break down?
- It's broken.

656
00:29:00,490 --> 00:29:02,159
- It's broken.
- Yes.

657
00:29:02,159 --> 00:29:03,359
It's broken.

658
00:29:04,490 --> 00:29:05,730
Okay.

659
00:29:07,559 --> 00:29:09,629
What game do you like?

660
00:29:11,970 --> 00:29:14,339
- "Mario Bros."
- "Mario Bros."

661
00:29:14,700 --> 00:29:16,909
Doesn't Porfi look like Mario?

662
00:29:16,909 --> 00:29:18,240
He'll look exactly like him
if he wears overalls.

663
00:29:18,470 --> 00:29:21,849
- My sons play games.
- Yes. Mario. The kids play it.

664
00:29:22,309 --> 00:29:25,180
I guess it's a universal thing.
Boys love games.

665
00:29:25,349 --> 00:29:28,649
Kids play games on their dad's computers.
A virus gets into their computers.

666
00:29:28,649 --> 00:29:30,589
Or they break the computers.
So kids get scolded for that.

667
00:29:31,690 --> 00:29:32,720
There it is.

668
00:29:33,790 --> 00:29:35,329
I like "Mario Bros."

669
00:29:35,930 --> 00:29:38,129
Hey, you. Do you want to play a round?

670
00:29:39,059 --> 00:29:40,159
Go.

671
00:29:40,430 --> 00:29:41,500
That's...

672
00:29:44,629 --> 00:29:45,669
It's over.

673
00:29:46,040 --> 00:29:47,540
You have to jump.

674
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:49,569
- Try again. You have two lives.
- Okay.

675
00:29:49,569 --> 00:29:52,309
I'm not good at this.

676
00:29:52,309 --> 00:29:54,309
- My sons are good at this.
- I see.

677
00:29:54,540 --> 00:29:57,879
When I went to my relative's house
in the countryside,

678
00:29:58,280 --> 00:30:00,819
- That again?
- my cousin's room looked like that.

679
00:30:01,119 --> 00:30:03,220
So is your relative's house
in Bolivia or the Amazon?

680
00:30:03,220 --> 00:30:04,619
- Which one is it?
- You can only choose one.

681
00:30:04,619 --> 00:30:06,520
- Which one is closer?
- It's a mix of the two.

682
00:30:06,520 --> 00:30:10,430
Let me explain.
The house overlooks the Yeoju River.

683
00:30:10,430 --> 00:30:11,859
And there's Mount Yeoju.

684
00:30:12,960 --> 00:30:14,460
- Is it Bolmazon then?
- Yes.

685
00:30:14,460 --> 00:30:15,470
(It's a mix of Bolivia and the Amazon.)

686
00:30:15,470 --> 00:30:16,470
Bolmazon.

687
00:30:18,399 --> 00:30:19,540
So cute.

688
00:30:20,399 --> 00:30:21,909
- Your cat?
- Oh, my.

689
00:30:21,909 --> 00:30:23,770
- Are they kitties?
- He's raising those kitties.

690
00:30:23,770 --> 00:30:25,169
- They are so cute.
- Gosh.

691
00:30:25,909 --> 00:30:28,909
(The kitties are sleeping.)

692
00:30:29,210 --> 00:30:31,210
They are my kitties.

693
00:30:31,609 --> 00:30:34,349
Gosh. They are smaller than his palm.
They are adorable.

694
00:30:34,819 --> 00:30:36,149
- They were sleeping.
- Aren't they wildcats?

695
00:30:36,149 --> 00:30:37,220
They are kitties.

696
00:30:37,950 --> 00:30:39,559
- They are kitties.
- Gosh. They are so cute.

697
00:30:39,559 --> 00:30:41,960
Oh, my. Look at them.
They look like dolls.

698
00:30:41,960 --> 00:30:43,129
I felt bad for them.

699
00:30:43,129 --> 00:30:45,629
Their mom went out to hunt for food.

700
00:30:46,430 --> 00:30:47,730
Why did you feel bad?
She's coming back, though.

701
00:30:47,730 --> 00:30:50,329
- Right.
- Something could've happened to the mom.

702
00:30:53,540 --> 00:30:55,409
- I see. She must be cooking now.
- Okay.

703
00:30:55,409 --> 00:30:56,740
What's that? A furnace?

704
00:30:56,740 --> 00:30:58,339
His sister was cooking there.

705
00:30:58,339 --> 00:31:00,680
This house smells just like
my relative's house in the countryside.

706
00:31:00,680 --> 00:31:03,079
It's coming from the fire in the furnace.

707
00:31:03,079 --> 00:31:04,550
Did your relatives bake bread there?

708
00:31:04,710 --> 00:31:07,180
No. It's the smell of the furnace.

709
00:31:08,619 --> 00:31:09,849
(This time, he shows his children's room.)

710
00:31:09,849 --> 00:31:11,649
- I see. His kids sleep here.
- Yes, my sons.

711
00:31:11,690 --> 00:31:13,790
They study here too.

712
00:31:14,020 --> 00:31:15,589
- The oldest and the second-oldest.
- Yes.

713
00:31:15,589 --> 00:31:17,859
(The oldest, Elmer,
the second-oldest, Porfi Junior)

714
00:31:18,059 --> 00:31:20,000
- He's already studying.
- Yes.

715
00:31:20,359 --> 00:31:21,559
- Is that okay?
- Yes.

716
00:31:22,500 --> 00:31:24,000
Can I take a look?

717
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:25,169
A mini car.

718
00:31:25,169 --> 00:31:26,940
(Elmer is assembling a mini car.)

719
00:31:26,940 --> 00:31:28,240
This is an engine for the mini car.

720
00:31:29,869 --> 00:31:31,770
Elmer made this.

721
00:31:32,180 --> 00:31:34,309
Really? That's amazing.

722
00:31:34,510 --> 00:31:36,950
(Made by Elmer)

723
00:31:37,149 --> 00:31:39,180
I used to play with mini cars
when I was a kid too.

724
00:31:40,480 --> 00:31:41,950
Why do you have so many pencils?

725
00:31:42,319 --> 00:31:44,490
I have to draw...

726
00:31:44,490 --> 00:31:46,720
and color them too.
So I need a lot of them.

727
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:49,530
Really? Do you like to draw?

728
00:31:49,960 --> 00:31:50,960
Yes.

729
00:31:51,659 --> 00:31:54,359
You know what? I draw for a living.

730
00:31:55,230 --> 00:31:56,530
Did you draw this?

731
00:31:56,930 --> 00:31:58,230
- Did you paint this?
- Yes.

732
00:31:58,230 --> 00:31:59,940
Show them to him, son.

733
00:31:59,940 --> 00:32:01,339
Can I see?

734
00:32:01,639 --> 00:32:03,270
(Surprised)

735
00:32:03,270 --> 00:32:06,510
His oldest son liked to draw.

736
00:32:06,510 --> 00:32:08,339
And his drawings were quite polished.

737
00:32:09,950 --> 00:32:13,050
(Showing them off)

738
00:32:13,050 --> 00:32:14,450
Hold on. This...

739
00:32:14,819 --> 00:32:17,119
Did you use watercolor paint?

740
00:32:17,119 --> 00:32:19,589
Yes. I used that.

741
00:32:20,220 --> 00:32:21,290
Great job.

742
00:32:21,819 --> 00:32:24,889
You used watercolor paint for this.
But the texture...

743
00:32:25,329 --> 00:32:27,659
How should I put it?
It looks like acrylic paint.

744
00:32:28,230 --> 00:32:30,169
You can adjust the texture
however you want.

745
00:32:30,169 --> 00:32:31,569
- A lion.
- The lion looks great.

746
00:32:32,099 --> 00:32:34,139
(Elmer is showing a lot of potential.)

747
00:32:34,139 --> 00:32:35,970
You're very good.

748
00:32:36,309 --> 00:32:38,040
He's only ten years old.
So that's considered...

749
00:32:38,040 --> 00:32:39,609
- He's so talented.
- very good.

750
00:32:39,879 --> 00:32:41,940
I used to teach kids at an art school too.

751
00:32:41,940 --> 00:32:43,909
That's very good for a ten-year-old.

752
00:32:43,909 --> 00:32:45,819
- So his level would be advanced?
- He's 13 years old.

753
00:32:45,819 --> 00:32:46,980
- He's 13.
- But he's still good.

754
00:32:46,980 --> 00:32:48,680
- He's 13 years old.
- He's in 6th grade.

755
00:32:48,680 --> 00:32:50,419
Well, a 13-year-old
can pull that off more easily.

756
00:32:50,990 --> 00:32:54,419
But his drawings are polished.
I don't see any white spots.

757
00:32:54,419 --> 00:32:57,030
When you look at kids' drawings,
they stop working on it as they get tired.

758
00:32:57,030 --> 00:32:59,629
But he filled in all the details
and completed all the drawings.

759
00:32:59,629 --> 00:33:01,659
I could tell he was diligent.

760
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:04,030
(He gets up
after looking at Elmer's paintings.)

761
00:33:05,740 --> 00:33:06,940
What's this?

762
00:33:07,740 --> 00:33:10,669
- Gosh. It brings back my old memories.
- Goodness.

763
00:33:10,669 --> 00:33:12,540
So I have no choice
but to mention it again.

764
00:33:12,540 --> 00:33:14,480
When I went to the countryside,

765
00:33:14,480 --> 00:33:17,649
the guys in the countryside
always had a TV like this in their rooms.

766
00:33:17,649 --> 00:33:19,619
- Bolmazon.
- Seriously. I'm not lying.

767
00:33:19,619 --> 00:33:21,750
- They bought this clip.
- This video.

768
00:33:23,750 --> 00:33:25,859
Back then, we had PlayStation One.

769
00:33:25,859 --> 00:33:30,460
This is very old.
We had this for ten years.

770
00:33:30,730 --> 00:33:32,700
- You had it only for ten years?
- Yes.

771
00:33:32,960 --> 00:33:34,500
It looks like it's been here for 40 years.

772
00:33:34,500 --> 00:33:36,770
(Since 2012)

773
00:33:36,770 --> 00:33:40,139
I see. Gosh.
It looks just like my relative's house.

774
00:33:40,899 --> 00:33:44,569
The rooms, the smell of the furnace,
and the gaming machine.

775
00:33:45,139 --> 00:33:47,680
I saw a resemblance of my hometown
in the Amazon.

776
00:33:48,010 --> 00:33:49,909
But I saw a resemblance
of my hometown in Bolivia too.

777
00:33:50,379 --> 00:33:53,050
The residents in Yeoju
might not agree with me.

778
00:33:53,579 --> 00:33:56,190
This was my life in Gyesin-ri
where I grew up.

779
00:33:56,190 --> 00:33:59,260
In the 1990s, this was my life
in Gyesin-ri, Yeoju, Gyeonggi Province.

780
00:33:59,260 --> 00:34:01,490
I'm so serious.

781
00:34:02,430 --> 00:34:03,460
Okay.

782
00:34:03,460 --> 00:34:06,430
I shouldn't scrutinize
their rooms too much.

783
00:34:06,430 --> 00:34:09,200
They're reaching that rebellious phase.

784
00:34:09,829 --> 00:34:12,369
The kids might be sensitive. I'll leave.

785
00:34:12,369 --> 00:34:13,940
(He's sweet enough to worry
about their rebellious phase.)

786
00:34:15,770 --> 00:34:18,669
It looks just like the house I grew up in
when I was a kid.

787
00:34:19,780 --> 00:34:21,210
It's the same.

788
00:34:21,740 --> 00:34:26,149
Back in my country... My childhood.
It's the same.

789
00:34:26,149 --> 00:34:28,720
I'm so happy to live here...

790
00:34:29,950 --> 00:34:33,490
because all the things
this land gives me...

791
00:34:33,490 --> 00:34:36,290
- Porfi, sit.
- Yes.

792
00:34:37,829 --> 00:34:40,559
(He gets up as soon as he sits down.)

793
00:34:41,829 --> 00:34:44,129
(Is that an avocado?)

794
00:34:44,129 --> 00:34:46,770
It's not an avocado. It's a mango.

795
00:34:46,770 --> 00:34:48,399
- It was a mango.
- A mango.

796
00:34:48,399 --> 00:34:50,639
- The avocado trees are over there.
- Porfi...

797
00:34:50,639 --> 00:34:52,240
- bragged about his orchard...
- This is a mango tree.

798
00:34:52,409 --> 00:34:54,740
for about three hours.

799
00:34:55,079 --> 00:34:56,450
So I'm good now. No more of that.

800
00:34:56,450 --> 00:34:58,919
- Okay, Porfi.
- Yes.

801
00:34:58,919 --> 00:35:01,050
- This is coffee.
- Porfi is bragging about his fruit.

802
00:35:01,319 --> 00:35:02,849
- Coffee.
- Porfi is bragging about his fruit.

803
00:35:03,950 --> 00:35:05,990
- Porfi.
- This is coffee.

804
00:35:05,990 --> 00:35:07,559
Porfi. Coffee?

805
00:35:07,559 --> 00:35:09,089
- Coffee.
- Americano.

806
00:35:09,690 --> 00:35:12,030
- Coffee.
- A coffee tree is in front of his house.

807
00:35:12,030 --> 00:35:14,059
Then they are coffee beans?

808
00:35:14,059 --> 00:35:15,300
Yes, they are.

809
00:35:15,800 --> 00:35:18,700
(He's talking about the wild coffee tree.)

810
00:35:18,700 --> 00:35:21,300
Okay. Porfi. Good.

811
00:35:21,970 --> 00:35:25,109
- He seems very exhausted.
- You seem out of it.

812
00:35:25,609 --> 00:35:26,780
I need to rest.

813
00:35:27,440 --> 00:35:29,409
- Porfi.
- I...

814
00:35:29,579 --> 00:35:31,450
Porfi is so talkative.

815
00:35:32,109 --> 00:35:33,619
I want to rest.

816
00:35:33,619 --> 00:35:35,919
Porfi.

817
00:35:36,120 --> 00:35:38,550
(There he goes again.)

818
00:35:39,160 --> 00:35:43,760
(He still has a lot to show off.)

819
00:35:43,990 --> 00:35:45,359
Okay.

820
00:35:45,359 --> 00:35:46,899
He'll show us his kitchen.

821
00:35:48,800 --> 00:35:51,470
I wanted to stop
after checking out his sons' room.

822
00:35:51,470 --> 00:35:53,839
- This is it.
- Porfi is showing me the kitchen...

823
00:35:53,839 --> 00:35:56,010
regardless of what I want.

824
00:35:57,069 --> 00:35:59,410
By the way,
the kitchen smells just like...

825
00:35:59,410 --> 00:36:01,879
the house in the countryside back home.

826
00:36:01,879 --> 00:36:03,410
- Back then, the wall...
- Right.

827
00:36:05,010 --> 00:36:06,979
Porfi! A gun.

828
00:36:08,450 --> 00:36:09,519
You...

829
00:36:11,990 --> 00:36:14,660
(Skilled)

830
00:36:15,089 --> 00:36:17,089
Porfi. You...

831
00:36:17,089 --> 00:36:20,100
This is for hunting.

832
00:36:20,300 --> 00:36:22,269
What do you hunt with the gun?

833
00:36:22,269 --> 00:36:24,229
Wild pheasant.

834
00:36:24,229 --> 00:36:25,229
Wild pheasant.

835
00:36:25,229 --> 00:36:27,999
- He's allowed to have a gun, right?
- It must've been uncomfortable.

836
00:36:27,999 --> 00:36:29,069
I don't know.

837
00:36:29,069 --> 00:36:30,339
- Do Yeon.
- Is it for protection?

838
00:36:30,339 --> 00:36:31,669
In Bolivia,

839
00:36:31,669 --> 00:36:34,240
people are allowed to have rifles
for hunting purposes.

840
00:36:34,240 --> 00:36:35,310
- For hunting.
- Yes.

841
00:36:35,310 --> 00:36:38,209
He told me he hunted pheasants
and cooked them for food.

842
00:36:38,209 --> 00:36:40,280
- Pheasant.
- You can't get fried chicken delivered.

843
00:36:40,280 --> 00:36:42,720
- Right. There...
- So they hunt pheasants.

844
00:36:42,720 --> 00:36:44,919
- Just like how we order delivery food,
- Right.

845
00:36:44,919 --> 00:36:46,890
- they shoot pheasant with their rifles.
- They do that right away.

846
00:36:46,890 --> 00:36:48,720
Then they must have pheasant
and beer together.

847
00:36:48,720 --> 00:36:50,030
- Pheasant and beer.
- Pheasant and beer.

848
00:36:50,030 --> 00:36:51,959
- Or pheasant and rice.
- Pheasant and rice.

849
00:36:52,430 --> 00:36:53,700
Pheasant and rice, not chicken and rice.

850
00:36:53,700 --> 00:36:55,300
- Fried pheasant.
- They are tasty too.

851
00:36:55,300 --> 00:36:56,870
- Fried pheasant. Seasoned pheasant.
- Seasoned pheasant.

852
00:36:57,229 --> 00:36:59,200
I mean, I knew we were all the same.

853
00:36:59,769 --> 00:37:03,010
Who knew there would be a house in Bolivia
resembling the house in my hometown?

854
00:37:03,439 --> 00:37:05,709
We should film the next episode
in your hometown.

855
00:37:05,709 --> 00:37:07,709
- I'm so curious.
- But a lot has changed now.

856
00:37:07,709 --> 00:37:09,010
Let's do it in your relative's house.

857
00:37:09,010 --> 00:37:10,209
- It changed a lot.
- I'm curious.

858
00:37:10,209 --> 00:37:12,519
- That's the oven.
- The oven.

859
00:37:12,720 --> 00:37:13,850
The furnace.

860
00:37:13,850 --> 00:37:14,979
- Did you have that in Yeoju?
- The furnace.

861
00:37:14,979 --> 00:37:17,019
- The furnace?
- We had a furnace.

862
00:37:17,519 --> 00:37:20,919
We're going to cook chicken
in the furnace.

863
00:37:21,359 --> 00:37:23,459
- We'll use the stones here.
- Really?

864
00:37:23,459 --> 00:37:24,459
(Porfi doesn't hesitate.)

865
00:37:24,459 --> 00:37:25,999
- That's... Gosh.
- That must be hot.

866
00:37:25,999 --> 00:37:27,260
Why did he put his hand in there?

867
00:37:27,260 --> 00:37:29,430
We're going to use the stones here
to cook the chicken.

868
00:37:29,430 --> 00:37:31,269
Porfi, are you a good cook?

869
00:37:31,269 --> 00:37:32,269
Yes.

870
00:37:32,269 --> 00:37:34,539
I can cook pasta and everything.

871
00:37:34,539 --> 00:37:36,010
My wife helps me too.

872
00:37:36,010 --> 00:37:39,109
People who sound confident like him
are usually good at cooking.

873
00:37:39,109 --> 00:37:40,910
He was proud about his cooking.

874
00:37:41,209 --> 00:37:44,749
And thank you for inviting me to dinner.

875
00:37:44,979 --> 00:37:47,220
Thank you. I'll go and cook.

876
00:37:48,919 --> 00:37:50,189
I'll rest up now.

877
00:37:51,319 --> 00:37:53,390
Porfi. He's so chatty.

878
00:37:55,089 --> 00:37:56,589
He's so chatty.

879
00:37:57,830 --> 00:38:02,330
Seriously. He never stopped talking.

880
00:38:02,499 --> 00:38:06,769
That's why I felt bad.
I should have been friendly like him.

881
00:38:07,140 --> 00:38:09,609
But I was so out of it.

882
00:38:11,140 --> 00:38:12,979
Thank you for having me.

883
00:38:13,939 --> 00:38:14,979
(Make yourself at home.)

884
00:38:16,410 --> 00:38:18,350
(I should get some rest now.)

885
00:38:18,810 --> 00:38:21,350
- I should lie down for a bit.
- You must have been so tired.

886
00:38:21,479 --> 00:38:25,149
- Actually, I woke up at 6 a.m.
- Right.

887
00:38:25,149 --> 00:38:26,919
Wait. Did I wake up at 5 a.m.?

888
00:38:26,919 --> 00:38:28,419
Ever since you woke up...

889
00:38:29,060 --> 00:38:30,589
- I've been out.
- Gosh.

890
00:38:30,589 --> 00:38:32,660
I couldn't sleep at all in the car
because I was nervous.

891
00:38:32,660 --> 00:38:34,800
- Right.
- You were in the car for eight hours.

892
00:38:34,800 --> 00:38:36,200
- You hiked for an hour.
- Gosh.

893
00:38:36,200 --> 00:38:37,430
(He's fatigued
from the long trip and hike.)

894
00:38:37,430 --> 00:38:40,539
(But Porfi doesn't rest.)

895
00:38:41,939 --> 00:38:43,609
- Did you sleep there?
- I feel bad.

896
00:38:43,609 --> 00:38:46,010
- Did you sleep for a long time?
- I took a break.

897
00:38:47,379 --> 00:38:51,280
(He wakes up at the bustling sounds.)

898
00:38:53,080 --> 00:38:57,289
(The father and son
show up with something.)

899
00:38:57,289 --> 00:38:59,160
- Did it die?
- It bites.

900
00:38:59,160 --> 00:39:00,189
It's alive?

901
00:39:00,189 --> 00:39:01,660
Wait. I'll take a picture.

902
00:39:01,660 --> 00:39:02,760
Wait.

903
00:39:03,789 --> 00:39:04,859
Just now...

904
00:39:04,859 --> 00:39:05,959
(Is that a lizard?)

905
00:39:05,959 --> 00:39:07,160
Gosh. It's a lizard.

906
00:39:07,160 --> 00:39:08,399
- A lizard.
- A lizard.

907
00:39:08,399 --> 00:39:10,470
- That's cute.
- Lizards are super cute.

908
00:39:10,470 --> 00:39:12,939
- That's so tiny.
- This was really funny. Watch.

909
00:39:12,939 --> 00:39:14,999
- Why?
- I thought it was dead.

910
00:39:15,370 --> 00:39:17,010
- Let's release it.
- It played dead.

911
00:39:18,310 --> 00:39:19,379
- It relaxed its legs.
- Yes.

912
00:39:19,379 --> 00:39:20,379
- On purpose?
- Right?

913
00:39:20,379 --> 00:39:21,580
It played dead.

914
00:39:21,580 --> 00:39:23,580
- To run away.
- Right. Gosh.

915
00:39:23,580 --> 00:39:24,950
(I got you, didn't I?)

916
00:39:24,950 --> 00:39:26,620
- Four.
- So cute.

917
00:39:26,620 --> 00:39:27,649
Did you catch it?

918
00:39:29,720 --> 00:39:32,189
(A tiny yet precious lizard)

919
00:39:32,189 --> 00:39:33,390
Let it live.

920
00:39:34,359 --> 00:39:35,359
That's cute.

921
00:39:36,359 --> 00:39:38,229
- Kian84.
- Porfi.

922
00:39:38,390 --> 00:39:40,899
You should sleep in the master bedroom.

923
00:39:41,200 --> 00:39:42,769
Where will you sleep, Porfi?

924
00:39:42,769 --> 00:39:45,430
I'm going to sleep outside.

925
00:39:45,430 --> 00:39:48,140
- He's so sweet.
- He's so kind.

926
00:39:48,240 --> 00:39:49,640
I can sleep on the floor.

927
00:39:49,870 --> 00:39:52,910
I'll sleep on the floor
between your sons' beds.

928
00:39:53,609 --> 00:39:57,280
I'm not that uncivilized.
I have some manners too. How can I?

929
00:39:57,410 --> 00:39:58,749
I wasn't comfortable...

930
00:39:58,749 --> 00:40:01,919
- making his wife sleep outside.
- Right.

931
00:40:01,919 --> 00:40:03,890
- You wouldn't feel good about it.
- Right.

932
00:40:03,890 --> 00:40:06,990
The bed? Okay.

933
00:40:07,289 --> 00:40:08,789
You got your wish.
You got to sleep in a tent.

934
00:40:08,789 --> 00:40:11,589
Wasn't that on your bucket list?
Sleeping at the top of the mountain?

935
00:40:11,589 --> 00:40:14,300
- Porfi didn't insist...
- No?

936
00:40:14,430 --> 00:40:15,999
when I said no.

937
00:40:15,999 --> 00:40:18,269
- I see. He should've insisted twice.
- He accepted it right away.

938
00:40:18,269 --> 00:40:19,499
- Right.
- That's how it is in Korea.

939
00:40:19,499 --> 00:40:21,800
- "But still. Sleep inside."
- "Sleep inside."

940
00:40:21,800 --> 00:40:23,839
- "It's okay."
- "Just sleep inside."

941
00:40:23,839 --> 00:40:25,569
- "It's okay."
- He should have insisted like this.

942
00:40:25,569 --> 00:40:27,240
Right. When I said I was fine...

943
00:40:27,240 --> 00:40:28,979
- "Okay"
- "How about a tent?"

944
00:40:29,140 --> 00:40:30,649
(Chuckling)

945
00:40:30,780 --> 00:40:32,680
You wanted to camp out overnight.

946
00:40:32,680 --> 00:40:34,749
I wanted to sleep
around the bonfire with Si Eon.

947
00:40:34,749 --> 00:40:37,720
But sleeping there alone was a bit sad.

948
00:40:39,289 --> 00:40:40,319
(He heads out to set up the tent.)

949
00:40:40,319 --> 00:40:43,189
People here don't say no
for the sake of formality.

950
00:40:44,160 --> 00:40:45,629
But this is more comfortable.

951
00:40:46,729 --> 00:40:48,999
This is the tent I wanted.

952
00:40:49,669 --> 00:40:53,269
Gosh. This will be perfect
with the sleeping bag Si Eon gave me.

953
00:40:55,470 --> 00:40:59,209
(He swiftly sets up the tent.)

954
00:41:01,240 --> 00:41:03,780
(Struggling)

955
00:41:05,209 --> 00:41:07,220
(She helps him after observing him.)

956
00:41:07,220 --> 00:41:08,319
Thank you.

957
00:41:08,879 --> 00:41:10,390
(Skillful)

958
00:41:10,390 --> 00:41:11,890
- She helped me out.
- Okay.

959
00:41:12,990 --> 00:41:14,120
Thank you.

960
00:41:15,490 --> 00:41:16,589
This is perfect.

961
00:41:16,589 --> 00:41:18,660
(Thanks to her,
he sets up his shelter in no time.)

962
00:41:19,229 --> 00:41:21,600
(And Si Eon gives him the sleeping bag
on the first day.)

963
00:41:21,859 --> 00:41:23,430
(I don't need this!)

964
00:41:23,899 --> 00:41:24,899
(He said he didn't need it.)

965
00:41:24,899 --> 00:41:26,339
I'm glad you listened to him.

966
00:41:26,339 --> 00:41:27,539
So you could use it that day.

967
00:41:27,539 --> 00:41:29,200
- That saved me from freezing to death.
- Gosh.

968
00:41:30,269 --> 00:41:32,839
(He finally has a chance
to use the sleeping bag.)

969
00:41:32,839 --> 00:41:35,140
What would you have done without Si Eon?

970
00:41:35,240 --> 00:41:36,379
This is my house.

971
00:41:37,310 --> 00:41:40,780
(He heads somewhere with a light heart.)

972
00:41:41,850 --> 00:41:44,050
(He arrives at the water tap in no time.)

973
00:41:44,550 --> 00:41:45,990
(He takes off his shirt as it's hot.)

974
00:41:45,990 --> 00:41:48,519
- I was so sweaty.
- Right.

975
00:41:48,959 --> 00:41:50,430
(He takes off his shirt.)

976
00:41:50,430 --> 00:41:52,600
The water must have been so cool.

977
00:41:52,660 --> 00:41:54,800
(He sticks his head in first.)

978
00:41:55,700 --> 00:41:56,769
(A man in the wild)

979
00:41:56,769 --> 00:41:59,499
Gosh. So manly! Look at his back muscles.

980
00:42:00,640 --> 00:42:02,539
(His manliness explodes.)

981
00:42:02,839 --> 00:42:05,640
(This is how a manly guy takes a shower.)

982
00:42:05,740 --> 00:42:08,410
Gosh. This is a clip
from "I Am a Natural Person."

983
00:42:08,410 --> 00:42:09,479
- Gosh.
- Goodness.

984
00:42:09,479 --> 00:42:11,680
(He's like a beast.)

985
00:42:13,249 --> 00:42:14,319
(Faltering)

986
00:42:14,319 --> 00:42:15,450
- That was cool.
- I slipped.

987
00:42:15,450 --> 00:42:17,550
- What was that?
- No, that was cool.

988
00:42:19,189 --> 00:42:20,720
(Faltering)

989
00:42:21,490 --> 00:42:25,089
(He continues taking a shower
as if nothing happened.)

990
00:42:25,229 --> 00:42:27,560
Gosh. He's gargling like that.

991
00:42:28,399 --> 00:42:29,569
Gosh. It's so cool.

992
00:42:30,169 --> 00:42:32,269
(After taking a cold shower,)

993
00:42:34,269 --> 00:42:37,039
(he wipes himself off
with the clothes he wore.)

994
00:42:37,510 --> 00:42:40,039
- Gosh. He's using it as a towel.
- His underwear.

995
00:42:40,280 --> 00:42:41,479
(That's so cool.)

996
00:42:41,479 --> 00:42:42,850
- That wasn't a towel?
- No.

997
00:42:42,850 --> 00:42:45,550
- I thought it had the same pattern.
- Right.

998
00:42:45,550 --> 00:42:47,979
- You do what you have to do!
- What a cool guy.

999
00:42:47,979 --> 00:42:49,749
People don't do that even in the military.

1000
00:42:49,749 --> 00:42:50,990
I'm a man!

1001
00:42:51,050 --> 00:42:52,149
- That.
- That's crazy.

1002
00:42:52,319 --> 00:42:54,060
Goodness. The sun went down so quickly.

1003
00:42:54,060 --> 00:42:55,289
(The sun has gone down during his shower.)

1004
00:42:55,490 --> 00:42:56,589
Gosh.

1005
00:42:56,589 --> 00:42:58,689
(He puts on the clothes
he tossed earlier.)

1006
00:42:59,260 --> 00:43:01,800
(He's going to wash his clothes.)

1007
00:43:02,870 --> 00:43:04,030
(Half-hearted)

1008
00:43:04,169 --> 00:43:05,669
(He's washing his socks.)

1009
00:43:05,669 --> 00:43:07,939
(But the socks have lost their color.)

1010
00:43:07,999 --> 00:43:09,470
- Isn't that the mood light?
- I didn't have detergent.

1011
00:43:10,339 --> 00:43:11,939
- Right?
- A rotten mushroom.

1012
00:43:11,939 --> 00:43:13,510
- He's washing it there.
- A mood light.

1013
00:43:13,510 --> 00:43:14,680
A rotten-mushroom light.

1014
00:43:16,350 --> 00:43:17,879
(He washes the mood light,)

1015
00:43:17,879 --> 00:43:19,249
(hoping it would regain its color.)

1016
00:43:20,249 --> 00:43:22,180
(Is he done?)

1017
00:43:22,280 --> 00:43:23,749
My clothes are soaked in sweat.

1018
00:43:24,350 --> 00:43:25,950
Gosh. Look at the collar.

1019
00:43:28,220 --> 00:43:30,589
- You didn't have detergent?
- He's just doing it by hand.

1020
00:43:30,830 --> 00:43:33,260
(That's how...)

1021
00:43:33,260 --> 00:43:34,729
(our moms used to wash clothes.)

1022
00:43:35,260 --> 00:43:36,300
You didn't have detergent, right?

1023
00:43:36,300 --> 00:43:37,729
I didn't want to use detergent.

1024
00:43:37,729 --> 00:43:39,229
I didn't want to harm the environment.

1025
00:43:40,069 --> 00:43:41,769
(He puts down the washed clothes.)

1026
00:43:42,640 --> 00:43:44,939
(He puts down
his only pair of socks as well.)

