01:04:04,660 --> 01:04:06,560
(Shaking)

1537
01:04:06,689 --> 01:04:09,200
It's for the guests.

1538
01:04:09,930 --> 01:04:11,769
Why am I walking on eggshells?

1539
01:04:12,430 --> 01:04:15,700
- I feel bad in front of his wife.
- Gosh.

1540
01:04:15,899 --> 01:04:17,410
I'm sorry.

1541
01:04:17,410 --> 01:04:18,669
(It's okay.)

1542
01:04:19,370 --> 01:04:22,039
This makes me feel uncomfortable.

1543
01:04:22,180 --> 01:04:24,749
- I'll give you a little, so taste it.
- Okay.

1544
01:04:25,780 --> 01:04:28,780
(Alcohol made with mandarins and honey)

1545
01:04:29,149 --> 01:04:31,350
I made it here.

1546
01:04:31,350 --> 01:04:33,649
Porfi, you transformed it?

1547
01:04:34,120 --> 01:04:35,160
Wow.

1548
01:04:35,589 --> 01:04:36,660
(Turning)

1549
01:04:36,660 --> 01:04:38,859
- He keeps glancing at her.
- I'm sorry.

1550
01:04:39,129 --> 01:04:40,660
(Okay.)

1551
01:04:40,859 --> 01:04:42,530
- A little?
- Yes.

1552
01:04:42,530 --> 01:04:44,200
It's quite thick.

1553
01:04:45,100 --> 01:04:46,600
He's mixing it.

1554
01:04:47,800 --> 01:04:50,470
- Cheers for life.
- Cheers for life.

1555
01:04:50,470 --> 01:04:51,740
It's nice to meet you,

1556
01:04:51,740 --> 01:04:54,680
and I hope you remember this
when you're in Korea.

1557
01:04:55,010 --> 01:04:57,450
Thank you.

1558
01:04:57,450 --> 01:04:58,450
(He feels great.)

1559
01:04:59,979 --> 01:05:01,180
Study hard.

1560
01:05:01,180 --> 01:05:02,479
(Like all middle-aged men,
he tells them to study hard.)

1561
01:05:02,720 --> 01:05:04,950
- Gosh.
- That looks delicious.

1562
01:05:04,950 --> 01:05:06,289
(The adults enjoy their time.)

1563
01:05:06,850 --> 01:05:08,789
(This is it.)

1564
01:05:09,490 --> 01:05:10,560
He's walking on eggshells.

1565
01:05:10,560 --> 01:05:13,530
His wife doesn't look happy.

1566
01:05:13,760 --> 01:05:15,999
(Thanks to Kian84,)

1567
01:05:16,300 --> 01:05:18,569
(he's allowed to break away today.)

1568
01:05:20,169 --> 01:05:21,470
Porfi.

1569
01:05:22,899 --> 01:05:23,899
I feel lonely.

1570
01:05:25,939 --> 01:05:29,510
(Loneliness as long-lasting
as altitude sickness)

1571
01:05:30,240 --> 01:05:31,550
There he goes again.

1572
01:05:33,780 --> 01:05:37,519
(He complained about loneliness
on the first day of the trip.)

1573
01:05:38,019 --> 01:05:39,490
It's because he's in front
of a nice family.

1574
01:05:39,490 --> 01:05:43,419
I was jealous that he had children.

1575
01:05:44,160 --> 01:05:45,160
(He gets up again.)

1576
01:05:45,160 --> 01:05:46,760
- Suddenly?
- One more bottle?

1577
01:05:46,890 --> 01:05:47,930
You...

1578
01:05:47,930 --> 01:05:49,100
(What's going on?)

1579
01:05:49,999 --> 01:05:52,729
I will play an instrument.

1580
01:05:53,300 --> 01:05:55,700
- To go with the alcohol...
- It's Kim Kwang Suk of Bolivia.

1581
01:05:55,899 --> 01:05:59,140
As Kian84 said that he's lonely,
he'll comfort him.

1582
01:05:59,709 --> 01:06:02,810
(Harmonica sounds spread out
in the middle of their meal)

1583
01:06:03,839 --> 01:06:05,550
(Getting up)

1584
01:06:05,950 --> 01:06:08,120
(Without listening,
she starts to clean up.)

1585
01:06:09,649 --> 01:06:11,789
(Dad is starting again.)

1586
01:06:13,149 --> 01:06:15,189
He keeps playing tactlessly.

1587
01:06:16,560 --> 01:06:18,390
(Finale)

1588
01:06:18,629 --> 01:06:20,330
(Exclaiming)

1589
01:06:20,330 --> 01:06:22,260
(Tired)

1590
01:06:22,260 --> 01:06:23,800
The same thing happened
when I was a child.

1591
01:06:23,800 --> 01:06:25,530
When dad came home with his friends,

1592
01:06:25,530 --> 01:06:27,100
he sang...

1593
01:06:27,100 --> 01:06:29,039
- and his friends clapped for him.
- He brought out alcohol.

1594
01:06:29,039 --> 01:06:31,339
Mom took out her anger on us.

1595
01:06:31,339 --> 01:06:33,870
She can't tell his friends to leave,

1596
01:06:33,870 --> 01:06:37,749
but dad's friends are tactless
and don't leave.

1597
01:06:37,879 --> 01:06:39,950
Look at the children's faces.

1598
01:06:39,950 --> 01:06:41,879
- That's the dad's friend.
- He's doing it again.

1599
01:06:41,879 --> 01:06:43,319
Imagine how they must feel.

1600
01:06:43,319 --> 01:06:44,649
"When is he leaving?"

1601
01:06:44,649 --> 01:06:46,390
- "We have to sleep."
- I feel bad.

1602
01:06:47,459 --> 01:06:48,760
(Only they're enjoying it.)

1603
01:06:48,760 --> 01:06:50,859
Beautiful. Good.

1604
01:06:51,830 --> 01:06:53,660
You're good at it.

1605
01:06:53,959 --> 01:06:57,229
Did you make your wife fall in love
with you with this?

1606
01:06:57,399 --> 01:06:58,899
(Flustered)

1607
01:06:59,669 --> 01:07:01,870
(He's speechless for a moment.)

1608
01:07:02,339 --> 01:07:03,839
Be honest.

1609
01:07:03,839 --> 01:07:06,039
I had many women.

1610
01:07:06,439 --> 01:07:08,410
(He's being too honest.)

1611
01:07:08,410 --> 01:07:10,410
I had many women.

1612
01:07:11,180 --> 01:07:12,850
(He's worried about Porfi being honest
while drunk.)

1613
01:07:14,120 --> 01:07:16,580
(Sighing)

1614
01:07:16,819 --> 01:07:19,249
- I met about 27 women.
- What?

1615
01:07:19,249 --> 01:07:23,260
- However, I never fell in love...
- He's talking too much.

1616
01:07:23,260 --> 01:07:26,359
with them like I did with her.

1617
01:07:26,530 --> 01:07:30,060
A moment ago, you said
that she was your first woman.

1618
01:07:30,060 --> 01:07:34,970
As I love her, we have three sons.

1619
01:07:35,300 --> 01:07:36,669
Who liked the other first?

1620
01:07:36,999 --> 01:07:40,370
My wife liked me more.

1621
01:07:40,640 --> 01:07:42,310
(Honey...)

1622
01:07:42,310 --> 01:07:44,350
Is it correct?

1623
01:07:44,350 --> 01:07:46,280
- Yes.
- Really?

1624
01:07:46,910 --> 01:07:48,649
What's the reason?

1625
01:07:48,649 --> 01:07:50,580
I should have brought it up
after putting them to bed.

1626
01:07:50,580 --> 01:07:52,890
He's quite drunk. Goodness.

1627
01:07:54,660 --> 01:07:55,760
Aren't you bored?

1628
01:07:55,760 --> 01:07:57,789
You should go to sleep. I'm sorry.

1629
01:07:57,930 --> 01:08:01,459
They should go to bed
since we're just talking.

1630
01:08:01,459 --> 01:08:03,899
- Go inside.
- Go to bed.

1631
01:08:03,899 --> 01:08:06,069
Porfi the First and Porfi Junior.

1632
01:08:06,069 --> 01:08:07,169
Porfi the First?

1633
01:08:07,169 --> 01:08:09,039
- The one to his right is Porfi the First.
- Porfi the First and Porfi Junior.

1634
01:08:09,700 --> 01:08:11,740
You're the real future of this country.

1635
01:08:12,910 --> 01:08:14,310
They're so cute.

1636
01:08:14,310 --> 01:08:16,280
(The cute children go back inside first.)

1637
01:08:17,280 --> 01:08:19,249
This is great.

1638
01:08:19,609 --> 01:08:24,220
I'm so happy that you came to visit me.

1639
01:08:24,419 --> 01:08:25,789
He must be very happy.

1640
01:08:25,789 --> 01:08:28,459
I'm also happy to meet someone
of my age...

1641
01:08:28,689 --> 01:08:31,930
in such a faraway country.

1642
01:08:32,530 --> 01:08:35,430
(Elmer is playing the pipe in his room.)

1643
01:08:35,600 --> 01:08:38,269
Right. Elmer.

1644
01:08:38,530 --> 01:08:39,769
(He arrives when called by his dad.)

1645
01:08:39,769 --> 01:08:41,100
Play it for him.

1646
01:08:42,240 --> 01:08:44,169
(He starts playing the pipe.)

1647
01:08:44,410 --> 01:08:48,379
(Elmer listens to his dad.)

1648
01:08:49,310 --> 01:08:51,280
(A sudden talent show at night)

1649
01:08:51,280 --> 01:08:53,109
(Playing hard)

1650
01:08:53,249 --> 01:08:55,919
I should give him some allowance.

1651
01:08:56,180 --> 01:08:58,490
Right, you should take some out.

1652
01:08:58,720 --> 01:09:00,019
Come here.

1653
01:09:00,019 --> 01:09:01,089
(The uncle's wallet opens.)

1654
01:09:01,089 --> 01:09:03,120
- Here's some allowance.
- Thank you.

1655
01:09:03,120 --> 01:09:04,490
Tell your brother to come.

1656
01:09:05,260 --> 01:09:07,999
(Like adults giving allowance to children)

1657
01:09:08,899 --> 01:09:11,600
I realized why my dad's friends
gave me an allowance...

1658
01:09:11,600 --> 01:09:13,169
while drinking.

1659
01:09:13,169 --> 01:09:14,439
They were probably pleased.

1660
01:09:14,439 --> 01:09:16,499
It's the best thing at that age.

1661
01:09:16,499 --> 01:09:18,539
- That's true.
- Here's some allowance.

1662
01:09:18,870 --> 01:09:20,439
- Thank you.
- Ask your little brother to come.

1663
01:09:20,439 --> 01:09:23,479
(He never looked happier today.)

1664
01:09:24,010 --> 01:09:26,050
(He tells his brother what happened.)

1665
01:09:26,580 --> 01:09:28,050
(Hurry.)

1666
01:09:29,220 --> 01:09:31,319
All right.

1667
01:09:31,749 --> 01:09:34,019
I'm giving it to you.

1668
01:09:34,519 --> 01:09:36,620
- Thank you.
- Be a good son.

1669
01:09:36,620 --> 01:09:37,689
- Thank you.
- Sure.

1670
01:09:37,689 --> 01:09:38,789
I'm giving you some pocket money.

1671
01:09:38,789 --> 01:09:39,789
Sure.

1672
01:09:39,789 --> 01:09:41,399
Now go to sleep.

1673
01:09:41,399 --> 01:09:42,800
(Old men always tell you to go to sleep.)

1674
01:09:42,800 --> 01:09:43,860
Goodnight.

1675
01:09:43,860 --> 01:09:46,129
It felt good when I gave them
some pocket money.

1676
01:09:46,129 --> 01:09:47,230
- Right.
- Of course.

1677
01:09:47,230 --> 01:09:49,369
Giving your nephew some money
makes you feel good.

1678
01:09:49,369 --> 01:09:51,239
I gave them the largest bills.

1679
01:09:51,239 --> 01:09:52,339
Good job.

1680
01:09:53,770 --> 01:09:54,810
Thank you.

1681
01:09:55,579 --> 01:09:58,150
(The adults are left
to spend more time together.)

1682
01:09:58,379 --> 01:09:59,709
Thank you, really.

1683
01:10:00,079 --> 01:10:02,650
I root for you, Porfi.

1684
01:10:04,220 --> 01:10:05,949
No, please.

1685
01:10:07,320 --> 01:10:09,289
- Porfi, come to Korea.
- Yes.

1686
01:10:10,459 --> 01:10:12,360
Come to Korea.

1687
01:10:12,760 --> 01:10:15,629
It's amazing...

1688
01:10:15,629 --> 01:10:19,169
how I met a friend my age in Bolivia.

1689
01:10:20,270 --> 01:10:21,570
(Holding hands)

1690
01:10:21,570 --> 01:10:22,940
You look a little tipsy.

1691
01:10:24,610 --> 01:10:26,739
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1692
01:10:26,739 --> 01:10:28,209
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

1693
01:10:29,480 --> 01:10:31,409
(Hugging)

1694
01:10:31,409 --> 01:10:33,709
You got attached overnight.

1695
01:10:33,709 --> 01:10:35,449
- I'm rooting for you.
- Thank you.

1696
01:10:36,550 --> 01:10:39,050
He's a guy my age living
on the other side of the world.

1697
01:10:39,320 --> 01:10:42,789
He was happier about it,
so I was thankful for that.

1698
01:10:43,190 --> 01:10:45,930
He has a good sense of humor.

1699
01:10:46,529 --> 01:10:49,529
(They're different, but they hit it off.)

1700
01:10:50,430 --> 01:10:53,169
(They shared their worlds
with each other for a day.)

1701
01:10:53,800 --> 01:10:58,010
He seems like a nice person.
We got a lot closer.

1702
01:10:58,940 --> 01:11:00,169
Porfi, goodnight.

1703
01:11:01,140 --> 01:11:02,180
- I'm going to sleep.
- Okay.

1704
01:11:02,180 --> 01:11:03,539
(They say goodnight
in front of their doors.)

1705
01:11:03,539 --> 01:11:04,579
Okay.

1706
01:11:04,680 --> 01:11:06,310
(Entering)

1707
01:11:06,310 --> 01:11:07,749
Life is the same everywhere.

1708
01:11:08,949 --> 01:11:10,050
Goodness.

1709
01:11:10,550 --> 01:11:11,720
Let's sleep.

1710
01:11:12,850 --> 01:11:15,320
(He feels too lazy to use his hands.)

1711
01:11:15,320 --> 01:11:16,820
He'll use his toes.

1712
01:11:16,820 --> 01:11:17,890
(His impressive toe movement)

1713
01:11:17,890 --> 01:11:19,690
As if we turn off the lights
with our feet.

1714
01:11:21,800 --> 01:11:22,930
(He failed to close the doors
with his foot.)

1715
01:11:22,930 --> 01:11:23,930
Gosh.

1716
01:11:25,400 --> 01:11:28,070
(He closes the tent tightly.)

1717
01:11:28,869 --> 01:11:31,209
(Now he's ready to sleep.)

1718
01:11:31,909 --> 01:11:33,610
(Lying down)

1719
01:11:34,610 --> 01:11:36,640
(He met a friend his age
in South America.)

1720
01:11:37,379 --> 01:11:40,850
(He goes to sleep happily,
thinking about their special friendship.)

1721
01:11:43,949 --> 01:11:49,760
(Snoring)

1722
01:11:50,489 --> 01:11:52,829
(It was windy at night,)

1723
01:11:53,190 --> 01:11:55,900
(but he could sleep deeply
as he didn't get altitude sickness.)

1724
01:11:56,860 --> 01:12:00,329
(The morning is coming in Bolivia.)

1725
01:12:01,199 --> 01:12:03,369
(The mountain birds,)

1726
01:12:03,369 --> 01:12:04,640
(the cats,)

1727
01:12:04,640 --> 01:12:05,810
- Oh, my.
- They're so cute.

1728
01:12:05,810 --> 01:12:08,079
(and a newborn baby)

1729
01:12:08,810 --> 01:12:12,209
(Everyone in Porfi's family is up.)

1730
01:12:13,110 --> 01:12:15,020
(But he's still sleeping like a rock.)

1731
01:12:15,020 --> 01:12:16,119
He kept sleeping.

1732
01:12:17,989 --> 01:12:19,190
(Knocking)

1733
01:12:19,190 --> 01:12:21,320
Kian84, good morning.

1734
01:12:21,320 --> 01:12:22,619
(Scratching)

1735
01:12:22,619 --> 01:12:23,690
- Kian84.
- Yes.

1736
01:12:24,629 --> 01:12:26,789
- Wake up now.
- Okay, Porfi.

1737
01:12:27,129 --> 01:12:29,930
Let's make coffee.

1738
01:12:29,930 --> 01:12:31,230
Okay.

1739
01:12:31,970 --> 01:12:32,970
Yes.

1740
01:12:32,970 --> 01:12:34,970
They wake up early there, right?

1741
01:12:34,970 --> 01:12:36,570
Yes, they do.

1742
01:12:36,570 --> 01:12:38,039
Even the sun comes up early.

1743
01:12:38,739 --> 01:12:41,510
It's only 6:30 a.m. Let me sleep.

1744
01:12:43,039 --> 01:12:45,379
(He's a sleepyhead.)

1745
01:12:45,579 --> 01:12:48,850
(Wake up, Uncle Kian84.)

1746
01:12:50,379 --> 01:12:51,419
Kian84.

1747
01:12:52,190 --> 01:12:54,520
I have handmade coffee you'd like.

1748
01:12:54,520 --> 01:12:56,020
Morning coffee.

1749
01:12:56,520 --> 01:12:58,230
At 7 a.m.?

1750
01:12:58,730 --> 01:13:00,430
Do you like coffee?

1751
01:13:00,430 --> 01:13:02,760
Coffee? Yes.

1752
01:13:04,129 --> 01:13:06,029
(Porfi mentioned coffee to wake him up,)

1753
01:13:06,270 --> 01:13:07,770
(but he went right back to sleep.)

1754
01:13:07,770 --> 01:13:09,499
Porfi is not even hungover.

1755
01:13:10,339 --> 01:13:12,339
(As Porfi doesn't have a hangover...)

1756
01:13:12,339 --> 01:13:13,510
How diligent.

1757
01:13:13,510 --> 01:13:15,810
Right. He harvested that.

1758
01:13:15,810 --> 01:13:17,209
It must feel so good to wake up...

1759
01:13:17,209 --> 01:13:19,449
- to the smell of coffee.
- Really.

1760
01:13:19,949 --> 01:13:21,180
How would that taste?

1761
01:13:21,180 --> 01:13:22,650
He did all that for him.

1762
01:13:23,279 --> 01:13:26,089
- Porfi is so sweet.
- Yes.

1763
01:13:26,089 --> 01:13:27,589
How thoughtful he is.

1764
01:13:27,919 --> 01:13:30,220
(Grinding)

1765
01:13:30,390 --> 01:13:32,159
(Opening his eyes)

1766
01:13:33,089 --> 01:13:35,529
I felt so bad that I had to get up.

1767
01:13:35,529 --> 01:13:36,600
Right.

1768
01:13:36,600 --> 01:13:38,900
(Puffy)

1769
01:13:38,900 --> 01:13:40,169
He ate a lot.

1770
01:13:40,499 --> 01:13:42,869
(You can tell how much he ate last night
from his puffy face.)

1771
01:13:44,300 --> 01:13:45,940
(He managed to get up.)

1772
01:13:45,940 --> 01:13:46,970
Hello.

1773
01:13:49,079 --> 01:13:50,180
What's that?

1774
01:13:51,980 --> 01:13:53,050
(He wets his hair first.)

1775
01:13:53,050 --> 01:13:54,110
How clean he is.

1776
01:13:55,050 --> 01:13:56,079
(Rubbing)

1777
01:13:56,079 --> 01:13:58,350
- I didn't have shampoo.
- You're only using water.

1778
01:13:58,350 --> 01:14:01,919
I can remove the grease
if I scrub enough with water.

1779
01:14:03,419 --> 01:14:06,489
(He uses his finger as a toothbrush.)

1780
01:14:06,489 --> 01:14:08,560
(Gargling)

1781
01:14:10,060 --> 01:14:11,770
(He washes his face...)

1782
01:14:11,770 --> 01:14:13,930
(and his ears.)

1783
01:14:14,640 --> 01:14:15,869
(He took a shower only with water.)

1784
01:14:15,869 --> 01:14:17,600
- He washed it all.
- That's amazing.

1785
01:14:19,039 --> 01:14:20,209
Is that a towel?

1786
01:14:20,209 --> 01:14:21,409
No, it's not. It's his shirt.

1787
01:14:21,409 --> 01:14:23,110
- It became his towel.
- Yes.

1788
01:14:23,339 --> 01:14:25,150
- If he dries that, it's a shirt again.
- Right.

1789
01:14:25,150 --> 01:14:26,810
It's a shirt when it's dry
and a towel when wet.

1790
01:14:26,810 --> 01:14:27,879
Right.

1791
01:14:29,520 --> 01:14:30,650
(Staggering)

1792
01:14:31,289 --> 01:14:33,690
(He staggers as he can't see
while drying his hair.)

1793
01:14:35,419 --> 01:14:36,959
(Feeling refreshed)

1794
01:14:38,659 --> 01:14:39,959
Look how wet his back is.

1795
01:14:39,959 --> 01:14:41,560
(Wet)

1796
01:14:41,900 --> 01:14:43,199
<i>Oh, Kian84</i>

1797
01:14:43,199 --> 01:14:45,329
<i>Let's eat now</i>

1798
01:14:46,300 --> 01:14:47,329
He sounds like an old man.

1799
01:14:47,329 --> 01:14:49,800
<i>Kian84, let's eat now</i>

1800
01:14:50,400 --> 01:14:52,270
- Kian84.
- Porfi.

1801
01:14:52,770 --> 01:14:54,209
Did you sleep well, Kian84?

1802
01:14:54,539 --> 01:14:56,279
- Did you sleep well?
- How are you?

1803
01:14:56,779 --> 01:14:57,949
I slept well.

1804
01:14:58,779 --> 01:15:01,449
- Porfi really likes him.
- Yes.

1805
01:15:02,220 --> 01:15:04,749
This is what we're going to drink.

1806
01:15:04,749 --> 01:15:05,989
What?

1807
01:15:07,720 --> 01:15:09,659
- Coffee?
- Coffee.

1808
01:15:11,860 --> 01:15:14,190
(While the adults are talking
in the morning,)

1809
01:15:14,959 --> 01:15:18,669
(the kids are getting ready
to go to school.)

1810
01:15:19,930 --> 01:15:23,270
(The oldest son comes out
to go to school first.)

1811
01:15:24,239 --> 01:15:26,810
- Kian84, they're going to school.
- Yes.

1812
01:15:26,810 --> 01:15:27,810
I see.

1813
01:15:27,810 --> 01:15:29,409
- They'll go on the zipline again.
- Yes.

1814
01:15:29,409 --> 01:15:30,610
- They're going to school.
- Study hard.

1815
01:15:30,610 --> 01:15:32,379
(Study hard!)

1816
01:15:32,379 --> 01:15:33,510
How brave you are.

1817
01:15:35,520 --> 01:15:38,690
He's seeing him off to school.

1818
01:15:39,550 --> 01:15:40,550
(Wearing a harness)

1819
01:15:40,550 --> 01:15:43,060
He'll only rely on that one cord.

1820
01:15:43,690 --> 01:15:44,930
Be a good student.

1821
01:15:44,930 --> 01:15:47,089
(They also tie his bag tightly.)

1822
01:15:49,860 --> 01:15:51,699
- He'll grow up to be strong.
- Right.

1823
01:15:51,699 --> 01:15:52,930
(Without hesitation)

1824
01:15:52,930 --> 01:15:54,029
He left.

1825
01:15:54,029 --> 01:15:55,600
(He goes to school over the gorge.)

1826
01:15:55,600 --> 01:15:56,839
He's not even wearing gloves.

1827
01:15:58,470 --> 01:16:02,510
There is no seat for the zipline.

1828
01:16:02,510 --> 01:16:04,379
It's just a piece of cloth.

1829
01:16:04,379 --> 01:16:06,510
- He made a knot with the cloth.
- He tied the cloth.

1830
01:16:07,050 --> 01:16:10,480
That's how they go to school.

1831
01:16:11,589 --> 01:16:14,890
(It slows down in the middle.)

1832
01:16:15,720 --> 01:16:18,159
(He pulls the cable to go forward.)

1833
01:16:18,159 --> 01:16:19,459
- With one hand?
- He has to do that.

1834
01:16:19,930 --> 01:16:21,430
Do you have to pull that?

1835
01:16:23,860 --> 01:16:25,230
How tough he is.

1836
01:16:27,199 --> 01:16:30,369
(After pulling dozens of times,)

1837
01:16:30,369 --> 01:16:32,409
The kids are really courageous.

1838
01:16:32,409 --> 01:16:33,810
(he finally steps on the ground.)

1839
01:16:33,810 --> 01:16:34,879
Oh, my.

1840
01:16:38,050 --> 01:16:41,520
- It looks dangerous to us.
- Yes.

1841
01:16:41,919 --> 01:16:45,150
But for them, it's their culture
and something common there.

1842
01:16:45,150 --> 01:16:46,150
- It's their life.
- Right.

1843
01:16:46,150 --> 01:16:47,249
Yes. Their life.

1844
01:16:47,249 --> 01:16:50,459
Actually, it's not just here
where they use ziplines.

1845
01:16:50,459 --> 01:16:53,390
Many people in South America
living at high altitudes use ziplines.

1846
01:16:53,390 --> 01:16:54,829
- Really?
- Yes.

1847
01:16:54,829 --> 01:16:57,560
Just like in Bolivia,
children in Colombia...

1848
01:16:57,560 --> 01:16:59,699
- also get around by zipline.
- They use it a lot.

1849
01:16:59,699 --> 01:17:03,400
It's because it's so mountainous there.

1850
01:17:03,400 --> 01:17:04,400
That's why.

1851
01:17:05,970 --> 01:17:08,180
(The second-oldest son gets ready
to leave for school next.)

1852
01:17:08,180 --> 01:17:09,779
I'm a little worried about him.

1853
01:17:10,279 --> 01:17:13,409
Do they go to the same school?

1854
01:17:13,409 --> 01:17:16,150
My oldest son goes to a different school.

1855
01:17:16,150 --> 01:17:19,789
He's still in elementary school.

1856
01:17:19,789 --> 01:17:21,520
Then your oldest son is in middle school.

1857
01:17:26,430 --> 01:17:28,300
He also gets ready quietly.

1858
01:17:28,300 --> 01:17:30,260
- They're so brave.
- I know.

1859
01:17:30,529 --> 01:17:32,600
- Why is it so touching?
- Right?

1860
01:17:33,400 --> 01:17:35,470
Porfi Junior, take care.

1861
01:17:36,800 --> 01:17:37,869
He's cute.

1862
01:17:38,140 --> 01:17:39,839
- Bye.
- Bye.

1863
01:17:41,610 --> 01:17:42,940
(After a short goodbye,)

1864
01:17:42,940 --> 01:17:44,510
(he leaves for school.)

1865
01:17:44,510 --> 01:17:45,579
There he goes.

1866
01:17:49,850 --> 01:17:53,050
(He crosses the forest and the river...)

1867
01:17:53,050 --> 01:17:59,289
(to go to elementary school.)

1868
01:18:01,289 --> 01:18:02,900
Isn't he scared?

1869
01:18:03,959 --> 01:18:07,100
Their dad doesn't stop in the middle,

1870
01:18:07,100 --> 01:18:09,570
but the kids are so light
that they have to use their hands.

1871
01:18:09,970 --> 01:18:11,510
(Grinning)

1872
01:18:11,510 --> 01:18:13,539
- He's so cute. He just smiled.
- Yes.

1873
01:18:14,039 --> 01:18:16,510
(He doesn't get scared...)

1874
01:18:16,510 --> 01:18:19,779
(and pulls himself forward by hand,
little by little.)

1875
01:18:22,879 --> 01:18:27,350
They would have to travel for two hours
if they didn't have that.

1876
01:18:27,720 --> 01:18:29,220
It'd be hard to go to school.

1877
01:18:30,020 --> 01:18:31,989
He has to pull for a while.

1878
01:18:31,989 --> 01:18:33,159
- Oh, my.
- My goodness.

1879
01:18:38,270 --> 01:18:39,930
(He has to walk for 30 minutes
to school even after ziplining.)

1880
01:18:39,930 --> 01:18:41,270
He walks for another 30 minutes.

1881
01:18:41,669 --> 01:18:42,940
I felt a little moved...

1882
01:18:43,669 --> 01:18:47,339
when I sent them to school on the zipline.

1883
01:18:47,640 --> 01:18:50,980
- They use the zipline on rainy days too.
- Yes.

1884
01:18:50,980 --> 01:18:53,879
- They can't take a detour.
- Right.

1885
01:18:54,010 --> 01:18:57,749
The kids used something
that looked like a sack.

1886
01:18:57,749 --> 01:18:59,220
- Yes. Like a piece of cloth.
- Yes.

1887
01:18:59,220 --> 01:19:01,619
The cloth was like a burlap sack.

1888
01:19:01,619 --> 01:19:05,529
- It looked worn out and dangerous,
- Of course.

1889
01:19:05,529 --> 01:19:08,029
so the production crew got them
a new harness.

1890
01:19:08,029 --> 01:19:09,029
A harness.

1891
01:19:09,029 --> 01:19:11,129
(A new harness)

1892
01:19:11,669 --> 01:19:15,100
(Thank you, Adventure by Accident)

1893
01:19:15,640 --> 01:19:16,900
(After sending the kids to school safely)

1894
01:19:16,900 --> 01:19:18,310
- Kian84.
- Yes.

1895
01:19:18,310 --> 01:19:19,470
Porfi.

1896
01:19:19,570 --> 01:19:22,409
- Let's drink our coffee.
- Coffee?

1897
01:19:22,579 --> 01:19:24,810
(The adults will have breakfast together.)

1898
01:19:24,810 --> 01:19:28,150
The kids have breakfast at school.

1899
01:19:28,379 --> 01:19:30,220
- Is it provided by the schools?
- Yes.

1900
01:19:30,220 --> 01:19:31,919
Breakfast.

1901
01:19:32,520 --> 01:19:34,249
He also toasted bread.

1902
01:19:34,249 --> 01:19:35,489
Thank you.

1903
01:19:35,789 --> 01:19:38,959
Is it from them?

1904
01:19:39,230 --> 01:19:41,659
(He used fresh coffee beans from them.)

1905
01:19:41,659 --> 01:19:42,860
Sit down.

1906
01:19:42,860 --> 01:19:45,430
(Freshly brewed Bolivian coffee)

1907
01:19:45,430 --> 01:19:46,869
What would it taste like?

1908
01:19:49,600 --> 01:19:51,070
(Startled)

1909
01:19:51,369 --> 01:19:52,739
Is that a spider web?

1910
01:19:53,839 --> 01:19:55,010
- Is there a bug?
- Yes.

1911
01:19:55,010 --> 01:19:56,180
He added a spider.

1912
01:19:56,180 --> 01:19:58,480
- In case he chokes while gulping it down.
- In case he chokes?

1913
01:19:58,709 --> 01:20:01,279
(He added a spider so that Kian84
doesn't choke on his coffee.)

1914
01:20:02,079 --> 01:20:04,449
- Is it good?
- It's good.

1915
01:20:04,650 --> 01:20:06,119
The morning coffee was good.

1916
01:20:06,119 --> 01:20:08,020
- How was it? Was it delicious?
- It was good.

1917
01:20:08,119 --> 01:20:09,890
It woke me up.

1918
01:20:10,390 --> 01:20:14,730
I even made this with my own hands.

1919
01:20:14,930 --> 01:20:16,360
- This too?
- Yes.

1920
01:20:17,230 --> 01:20:21,970
Did you also harvest the wheat?

1921
01:20:22,300 --> 01:20:24,570
- No.
- You bought the wheat.

1922
01:20:26,640 --> 01:20:28,279
Had he also harvested the wheat,
I would've been impressed.

1923
01:20:28,279 --> 01:20:30,539
- He bought the flour.
- He couldn't have made everything.

1924
01:20:30,539 --> 01:20:32,650
Porfi, do you work today?

1925
01:20:32,810 --> 01:20:34,949
Yes. Today...

1926
01:20:34,949 --> 01:20:37,419
I'll check the zipline wires...

1927
01:20:37,419 --> 01:20:40,820
as a checkup.

1928
01:20:41,789 --> 01:20:43,760
After finishing our coffee,

1929
01:20:43,959 --> 01:20:45,329
let's work.

1930
01:20:45,690 --> 01:20:47,890
- Okay. I'm glad.
- Okay?

1931
01:20:48,499 --> 01:20:50,529
(Porfi's new worker)

1932
01:20:51,100 --> 01:20:52,570
- Well...
- You'll help him with his work.

1933
01:20:52,570 --> 01:20:53,999
Just as I did in the Amazon,

1934
01:20:54,270 --> 01:20:55,539
I wanted to help him...

1935
01:20:55,539 --> 01:20:56,970
- Right.
- You should pay for the food.

1936
01:20:56,970 --> 01:20:58,409
- to return the favor.
- Yes.

1937
01:21:00,440 --> 01:21:01,739
How many days has it been?

1938
01:21:02,379 --> 01:21:04,480
I've lost count.

1939
01:21:05,150 --> 01:21:08,449
Porfi invited me to his house,

1940
01:21:08,449 --> 01:21:09,949
so I slept over there.

1941
01:21:10,919 --> 01:21:14,820
Do you see the rocks are not even?

1942
01:21:14,820 --> 01:21:16,360
The ground is uneven.

1943
01:21:16,360 --> 01:21:18,220
That hurt my back so much.

1944
01:21:18,959 --> 01:21:21,589
(Even though his back hurt,
he slept like a baby.)

1945
01:21:22,760 --> 01:21:24,230
So I had to...

1946
01:21:24,230 --> 01:21:25,900
(She's listening to Kian84 exaggerating.)

1947
01:21:25,900 --> 01:21:27,499
She finds it interesting.

1948
01:21:27,499 --> 01:21:30,239
She's so shy. She doesn't talk that much.

1949
01:21:30,369 --> 01:21:31,869
I see some cats over there.

1950
01:21:31,869 --> 01:21:33,270
Can I see the cats?

1951
01:21:35,110 --> 01:21:36,779
Oh, dear.

1952
01:21:37,239 --> 01:21:38,779
What do they eat?

1953
01:21:38,779 --> 01:21:40,150
(The baby cats warm your heart
in the morning.)

1954
01:21:40,180 --> 01:21:42,119
There are always cute animals here.

1955
01:21:42,119 --> 01:21:44,180
- How tiny they are.
- My gosh.

1956
01:21:44,379 --> 01:21:46,589
How cute you guys are.

1957
01:21:47,289 --> 01:21:49,520
- You're so adorable.
- They're so small.

1958
01:21:49,520 --> 01:21:51,760
- They're so cute.
- They must be a month old.

1959
01:21:51,760 --> 01:21:54,930
Let's do this. Help me.

1960
01:21:54,930 --> 01:21:56,029
Let's go.

1961
01:21:57,629 --> 01:21:58,730
(He starts checking the zipline.)

1962
01:21:58,730 --> 01:22:00,129
You're there to help him.

1963
01:22:00,129 --> 01:22:03,739
Yes. They have to check it often.

1964
01:22:03,739 --> 01:22:04,869
I can imagine.

1965
01:22:04,869 --> 01:22:06,909
- The most important mode of transport.
- Yes.

1966
01:22:07,669 --> 01:22:10,539
He's winding it so it's not slippery.

1967
01:22:10,539 --> 01:22:11,539
(He winds a rubber wire around it
to make it slip-resistant.)

1968
01:22:14,709 --> 01:22:15,949
Let me hold this.

1969
01:22:18,589 --> 01:22:20,619
He adjusts the wire.

1970
01:22:20,619 --> 01:22:21,860
(He adjusts the wire with a steel wire.)

1971
01:22:21,919 --> 01:22:23,419
Please hold this.

1972
01:22:24,690 --> 01:22:26,560
Pull it all the way.

1973
01:22:27,489 --> 01:22:30,300
(He twists the wire to secure it.)

1974
01:22:30,300 --> 01:22:31,699
I wanted to be more helpful,

1975
01:22:31,699 --> 01:22:34,070
- but it took a lot of skills.
- Right.

1976
01:22:34,070 --> 01:22:37,100
All I could do was hold things for him.

1977
01:22:37,270 --> 01:22:38,909
(Struggling)

1978
01:22:38,909 --> 01:22:40,369
One last time.

1979
01:22:42,379 --> 01:22:45,709
(He tightens the pin.)

1980
01:22:45,709 --> 01:22:46,949
I'll hold this.

1981
01:22:47,810 --> 01:22:50,550
- He tightens the screws by hand.
- He tightens them one by one by hand.

1982
01:22:51,020 --> 01:22:52,190
That's impressive.

1983
01:22:52,190 --> 01:22:55,190
(The assistant is adding his strength
by frowning.)

1984
01:22:55,459 --> 01:22:56,489
Here.

1985
01:22:57,119 --> 01:22:58,730
- Now he oils it.
- Goodness.

1986
01:22:58,959 --> 01:23:01,959
His family keeps using the zipline.

1987
01:23:01,959 --> 01:23:04,800
- Right. It's for his family's safety.
- Yes.

1988
01:23:05,369 --> 01:23:08,669
How often do you check the zipline?

1989
01:23:08,940 --> 01:23:11,039
I don't do it regularly.
I check once in a while.

1990
01:23:11,039 --> 01:23:14,339
I fix it whenever it gets loose.

1991
01:23:14,869 --> 01:23:17,140
Is there anything Porfi can't do?

1992
01:23:17,510 --> 01:23:19,480
- He doesn't sleep.
- He doesn't get a hangover either.

1993
01:23:19,480 --> 01:23:20,480
(Even though he drank last night,)

1994
01:23:20,879 --> 01:23:23,850
(he fixed the zipline easily.)

1995
01:23:24,579 --> 01:23:27,449
Porfi, is there anything else
I can help you with?

1996
01:23:27,820 --> 01:23:30,289
You let me stay and even fed me.

1997
01:23:30,390 --> 01:23:32,789
Let's go to Coroico.

1998
01:23:32,789 --> 01:23:35,260
- Okay.
- My second son goes to school there.

1999
01:23:35,260 --> 01:23:38,629
Let's pick him up after school
and go to Coroico.

2000
01:23:38,629 --> 01:23:40,199
Together?

2001
01:23:40,199 --> 01:23:41,730
Yes? Okay.

2002
01:23:41,900 --> 01:23:44,640
Coroico is like downtown.

2003
01:23:45,369 --> 01:23:47,409
- I was too sad to leave right away.
- It's good.

2004
01:23:47,409 --> 01:23:49,779
I thought I could have a meal
with him there.

2005
01:23:50,339 --> 01:23:53,610
He wants to meet up down there.

2006
01:23:53,879 --> 01:23:57,050
I'll get ready and go down.

2007
01:23:57,550 --> 01:24:01,489
Porfi,
let's meet at the end of the zipline.

2008
01:24:02,390 --> 01:24:04,289
- See you there.
- Okay.

2009
01:24:04,289 --> 01:24:06,060
I'll get ready and go there soon.

2010
01:24:06,190 --> 01:24:09,100
He'll go down first,
and Porfi will come down by zipline.

2011
01:24:09,230 --> 01:24:10,430
Ma'am, I should go.

2012
01:24:10,430 --> 01:24:11,529
(He says goodbye to his family.)

2013
01:24:11,529 --> 01:24:13,270
Yes. I'm going to go.

2014
01:24:13,270 --> 01:24:16,869
- Stay healthy.
- Be safe.

2015
01:24:17,039 --> 01:24:21,110
Come to Korea with Porfi someday.

2016
01:24:21,110 --> 01:24:23,110
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

2017
01:24:23,110 --> 01:24:25,749
We should take care
of Eric's family and Porfi's family.

2018
01:24:25,749 --> 01:24:27,749
- Yes.
- Right. He made two friends.

2019
01:24:27,749 --> 01:24:28,820
He did.

2020
01:24:29,180 --> 01:24:32,690
Hey, I have to go back.

2021
01:24:33,520 --> 01:24:36,860
Take care. I should get going.

2022
01:24:36,989 --> 01:24:39,260
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

2023
01:24:40,529 --> 01:24:44,459
I'll get ready and go down.

2024
01:24:45,470 --> 01:24:47,699
I feel like I imposed
on their hospitality. I feel bad.

2025
01:24:47,699 --> 01:24:51,140
I wish there was more
I could help him with.

2026
01:24:51,770 --> 01:24:52,970
Be happy.

2027
01:24:53,570 --> 01:24:54,640
Goodness.

2028
01:24:56,379 --> 01:25:00,980
(What will happen in Coroico?)

2029
01:25:03,050 --> 01:25:05,419
(Everything is on Uncle Kian84 today!)

2030
01:25:06,190 --> 01:25:07,690
(Tell me your wish.)

2031
01:25:07,989 --> 01:25:08,989
(Notebooks)

2032
01:25:08,989 --> 01:25:10,320
(A soccer ball)

2033
01:25:10,320 --> 01:25:11,489
(A backpack)

2034
01:25:11,720 --> 01:25:13,060
(He buys them all.)

2035
01:25:13,060 --> 01:25:14,459
(Uncle Kian84 is the best.)

2036
01:25:14,829 --> 01:25:16,300
(But...)

2037
01:25:16,300 --> 01:25:18,459
(he's struggling at the counter.)

2038
01:25:18,970 --> 01:25:20,699
(Uncle?)

2039
01:25:20,970 --> 01:25:22,140
(Can I get a discount?)

2040
01:25:22,140 --> 01:25:23,239
(Not at all.)

2041
01:25:23,470 --> 01:25:25,470
(Will he be able to pay?)

2042
01:25:26,070 --> 01:25:27,940
(Finally, the long-awaited destination...)

2043
01:25:28,169 --> 01:25:30,079
(of this journey)

2044
01:25:30,480 --> 01:25:33,050
(Where do you want to visit the most
in South America?)

2045
01:25:33,180 --> 01:25:35,550
(The Salt Flats!)

2046
01:25:35,949 --> 01:25:38,150
(The place you have to visit
before you die)

2047
01:25:38,150 --> 01:25:40,589
(Uyuni Salt Flats)

2048
01:25:42,190 --> 01:25:44,060
(It was eventful,)

2049
01:25:44,260 --> 01:25:46,230
(but they were happy together.)

2050
01:25:46,589 --> 01:25:48,730
(The 10 days of journey)

2051
01:25:49,430 --> 01:25:51,629
